{"title_page": "Jay Weinberg", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = si cgeng\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image            = Against Me! @ Dour 2012 (7875273172).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| caption          = Jay Weinberg performing with [[Against Me!]] in 2012.\n| birth_name       = Jay Weinberg\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Ballbag\n* J-peg\n}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1990|09|08}}\n| origin           = [[Middletown Township, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[nu metal]]\n* [[groove metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[alternative metal]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Drums\n* vocals\n}}\n| years_active     = 2000\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]\n* [[Hesitation Wounds]]\n* [[Madball]]\n* [[Against Me!]]\n* [[Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band]]\n* Bleed the Pigs \n}}\n| website          =\n}}\n\n'''Jay Weinberg''' (born September 8, 1990),<ref name=\"nsl-int\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2009/05/jay_weinberg_speaks_hockey_dru.html | title=Jay Weinberg speaks: hockey, drumming and the E Street Band | author=Lustig, Jay | newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]] | date=May 8, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> is an American musician and drummer for heavy metal band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]. He is the son of American drummer [[Max Weinberg]]. He has played with the American [[punk rock]] band the Reveling<ref name=rs>{{cite magazine|title=Springsteen's \"Secret Weapon\": How Jay Weinberg Scored a Spot in the E Street Band |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/03/27/springsteens-secret-weapon-how-jay-weinberg-scored-a-spot-in-the-e-street-band/ |date=March 27, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-15 |author=Greene, Andy |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> and toured in 2009 as a drummer with [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s [[E Street Band]], substituting for his father.<ref name=yahoo>{{cite news|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/1/20090322/ten-weinberg-to-be-replaced-by-his-son-o-c60bd6d.html |title=Weinberg to be replaced by his son on Springsteen shows in Europe |date=March 22, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-15 |work=[[Yahoo News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327094709/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/1/20090322/ten-weinberg-to-be-replaced-by-his-son-o-c60bd6d.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref> During 2010, he was briefly the drummer for [[Madball]]. During 2011 and 2012, Weinberg played with [[Against Me!]]. In 2014, Weinberg replaced [[Joey Jordison]] as the drummer for [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] and is currently the youngest member of the band.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWeinberg is the son of drummer [[Max Weinberg]], who joined the E Street Band in 1975;<ref name=yahoo/> his mother, Rebecca \"Becky\" (Schick), was a former teacher.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> He grew up in [[Middletown Township, New Jersey|Middletown Township]], New Jersey.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> His mother was a [[Methodist]] and his father [[Jewish]].<ref name=\"schleier\">{{cite news | title=E Street to Conan, Max Weinberg keeps on drumming | author=Schleier, Curt | newspaper=[[Jewish Bulletin of Northern California]] | date=February 6, 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"nt100307\">{{cite news | url=http://newstranscript.gmnews.com/news/2007/1003/Front_Page/040.html | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130102185042/http://newstranscript.gmnews.com/news/2007/1003/Front_Page/040.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=January 2, 2013 | title=A good cause for purrs and paws | author=Meggitt, Jane | newspaper=[[News Transcript]] | location=Monmouth County, New Jersey | date=October 3, 2007 }}</ref> His sister is Ali Weinberg Rogin (married to [[Josh Rogin]]).<ref name=Wedding>[http://washingtonlife.com/2016/04/18/society-weddings-ali-weinberg-and-josh-rogin/ Washington Life: \"Society Weddings: Ali Weinberg and Josh Rogin\" by John Arundel] April 18, 2016</ref> As a child, he played travel team [[ice hockey]] as a [[goaltender]].<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/><ref name=rs/><ref name=\"mst050909\">{{cite news | url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/44553222.html | title=The beat goes on | author=Bream, Jon | newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] | date=May 9, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-11 | page=1E | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007001745/http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/44553222.html | archivedate=October 7, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> At age 9 he first saw the E Street Band on their 1999\u20132000 [[Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band Reunion Tour|Reunion Tour]],<ref name=rs/> and saw shows on this and subsequent tours, especially in Europe.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> Around the same time his father took him to [[Ozzfest]] to see [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], which gave him a strong affinity for [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and other intense music genres;<ref name=mtv/> his father also exposed him to a wide variety of other music.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> He began playing guitar at age 9, bass at age 12 or 13.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> He then started playing drums at age 14, getting only few lessons from his father without much instruction and being mostly self-taught,<ref name=rs/><ref name=\"nsl051509\"/><ref name=\"nsl081309\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nj.com/insidejersey/index.ssf/2009/08/new_gig_same_beat.html#more | title=New Gig, but Same Beat for Drummer Max Weinberg | author=Tsai, Martin | newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]] | date=August 13, 2009 | accessdate=September 5, 2009}}</ref> using his father's old gear.<ref name=mtv/> By the next year he had performed a guest appearance on stage with band [[The Used]] and subsequently with [[punk rock]]ers [[the Bouncing Souls]].<ref name=rs/> He played in the New Jersey metal band Chaosis.<ref name=\"mst050909\"/> He attended [[Rumson-Fair Haven Regional High School]] where he played on the hockey team for a time, played in a band called Sadie Mae, and graduated in 2008.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/><ref name=\"nsl051509\"/>\n\nWeinberg graduated from [[Stevens Institute of Technology]] in [[New Jersey]] in 2014.<ref name=mtv>{{cite web |title=Jay Weinberg Feels 'Super Fortunate' To Play on Bruce Springsteen Tour |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1610571/20090504/springsteen_bruce.jhtml |date=May 4, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-15 |author=Wolfson, Melanie |publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MORE PHOTOS: Stevens graduates, including son of celebrity drummer, told to 'remain optimistic' |url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2014/05/more_photos_stevens_graduates_including_celebrity_drummer_told_to_remain_optimistic.html |date=2014-05-22 |author=Hortillosa, Summer Dawn |work=[[The Jersey Journal]] |accessdate=2015-12-29}}</ref> He joined the New York punk band the Reveling in August 2008, which plays before small audiences in venues such as the Ace of Clubs nightspot in Manhattan, various spots in Brooklyn, and elsewhere.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/><ref name=\"nsl051509\"/><ref name=\"ct061609\">{{cite news | url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/about-last-night/2009/06/springsteen-didnt-look-far-for-teenage-drummer-jay-weinberg.html | title=Springsteen didn't look far for teenage drummer, Jay Weinberg | author=Arroyave, Luis | newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=June 16, 2009 | accessdate=2009-07-31}}</ref> With them he does some of the band's songwriting and arranging.<ref name=\"nsl051509\"/>\n\n==Appearances with Springsteen==\n[[File:Max watches Jay Weinberg 2008.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Max Weinberg (standing in front of stage, in black shirt) watches son Jay on the video screen, during \"Born to Run\" at Giants Stadium in 2008]]\nJay Weinberg's first appearance with Springsteen was in the summer of 2008, filling in for his father on \"[[Born to Run (song)|Born to Run]]\" at [[Giants Stadium]] after having watched many other performances during the [[Magic Tour (Bruce Springsteen)|Magic Tour]].<ref name=rs/> Springsteen's 2009 [[Working on a Dream Tour]] posed a problem for Max Weinberg, as ''[[The Tonight Show with Conan O'Brien]]'' in Los Angeles \u2013 for which he was [[the Max Weinberg 7]] bandleader \u2013 was starting at the same time that the tour would be in progress.<ref name=\"bs-max09\">{{cite news | url=http://www.backstreets.com/news.html | title=Max Watch '09: A Tale of Two Bosses | publisher=[[Backstreets.com]] | date=January 16, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> Springsteen's manager [[Jon Landau]] viewed Weinberg as the \"secret weapon\" to substitute for his father without losing fan satisfaction.<ref name=rs/> Both Landau and E Street guitarist [[Steve Van Zandt]] attributed Jay Weinberg's skills to a genetic gift.<ref name=rs/><ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/03/springsteen-wei.html | title=Springsteen news: Steve Van Zandt talks about the E Street Band's new drummer | author=Brunner, Rob | magazine=[[EW.com]] | date=March 20, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref>\n\nOnce the initial portion of the tour began in early April 2009, Weinberg played from several songs to half the show on most of the dates.<ref name=mtv/><ref name=\"ct061609\"/><ref name=\"pl042209\">{{cite news | url=http://www.patriotledger.com/entertainment/x50626460/Boss-and-band-cover-a-lot-of-ground-in-Boston | title=Boss and band cover a lot of ground in Boston | author=Miller, Jay N. | newspaper=[[The Patriot Ledger]] | date=April 22, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref><ref name=\"gnr050409\">{{cite news | url=http://www.news-record.com/content/2009/05/03/article/3_hour_show_rocks_steensboro | archive-url=https://archive.is/20090505165230/http://www.news-record.com/content/2009/05/03/article/3_hour_show_rocks_steensboro | url-status=dead | archive-date=May 5, 2009 | title=Review: 3-hour show rocks 'Steensboro' | author=Puterbaugh, Parke | publisher=[[News & Record (Greensboro)|News & Record]] | date=May 4, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-10 }}</ref> He received a very positive reaction from both audiences and reviewers as a re-energizing \"spark plug\"<ref name=\"gnr050409\"/> for the much-older band,<ref name=\"atu051509\"/> with his vigorous, long-hair-flying style inviting comparisons to [[Dave Grohl]]<ref name=\"mc050209\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/music/all-d4_weekconcerts.6882370may02,0,2402026.story \n |title=Concert Reviews: Bruce Springsteen \n |author=Gehman, Geoff \n |newspaper=[[The Morning Call]] \n |date=May 2, 2009 \n |accessdate=2009-05-10 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521110511/http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/music/all-d4_weekconcerts.6882370may02%2C0%2C2402026.story \n |archivedate=May 21, 2009 \n}}</ref> and his potential for replacing his father drawing allusions to [[Wally Pipp]].<ref name=\"mst050909\"/><ref name=\"pl042209\"/> He began playing complete shows in mid-May 2009 during the tour's American first leg, as his father went to California to prepare test runs for ''The Tonight Show'' start.<ref name=\"nsl051509\"/><ref name=\"atu051509\">{{cite news | url=http://blogs.timesunion.com/reviews/?p=900 | title=Bruce Springsteen @ Times Union Center 5/14/09 | author=Eck, Michael | newspaper=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]] | date=May 15, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518180059/http://blogs.timesunion.com/reviews/?p=900 | archivedate=May 18, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' magazine's editor said that a college freshman playing on one of the year's biggest rock tours is \"certainly a unique story\".<ref name=\"nsl051509\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2009/05/born_to_drum_two_generations_o.html | title=Born To Drum: Two generations of Weinbergs do the E Street Shuffle | author=Lustig, Jay | newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]] | date=May 15, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> Weinberg played a number of dates early on in the European second leg of the tour, including at the Dutch [[Pinkpop festival]] in [[Landgraaf]], the [[Netherlands]] in addition to [[Bonnaroo]] in [[Manchester, Tennessee]].  He also played during a few dates of the American third and final leg.  When not needed for the Springsteen tour, he continued to play for the Reveling, often before audiences that were three orders of magnitude smaller; he said of the difference, \"I liked the duality of it all ... I like doing this just as much as I like doing that.\"<ref name=\"ct061609\"/>\n\n==Madball==\nIn February 2010, Weinberg began playing with [[Madball]], a legendary hardcore band based out of New York City.<ref name=\"prp-mad\"/> In June of that year, it was announced that he would become the drummer for their upcoming album ''[[Empire (Madball album)|Empire]]'' and a tour.<ref name=\"prp-mad\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theprp.com/2010/06/25/news/madball-recruit-new-drummer/ | title=Madball Recruit New Drummer | publisher=ThePRP.com | date=June 25, 2010 | accessdate=2010-06-25}}</ref> However, in September 2010 the group discharged him, with Madball vocalist [[Freddy Cricien]] saying, \"I'm letting Jay go [mid-tour] in Canada because I just feel he doesn't represent this band well on a character level.\"<ref name=\"blab1\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=146430 |title=Madball Fires Max Weinberg's Son |date=September 21, 2010 |accessdate=2010-09-21 |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926153955/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=146430 |archivedate=September 26, 2010 |df= }}</ref> In response, Weinberg said that he had already quit the group by that time, and that \"while I really enjoyed playing the music, I do not subscribe to their choice of habits and lifestyle. This past August while on tour in Europe, disturbing events within the band indicated to me that it was time for me to move on.\"<ref name=\"blab2\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=147874 | title=Ex-Madball Drummer Jay Weinberg Says He Quit The Band | date=October 18, 2010 | publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] | accessdate=2010-10-18 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022140111/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=147874 | archivedate=October 22, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In any case, Weinberg said both he and the group should be proud of ''Empire''.<ref name=\"blab2\"/>\n\n==Against Me!==\nIn November 2010, it was announced that Weinberg would be playing drums with punk rock band [[Against Me!]] for their upcoming 2011 shows, covering for regular drummer George Rebelo while he tours with his other band, [[Hot Water Music]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.the1stfive.com/news/against-me-leave-sire-records-address-cancelled-tour-issues-and-announce-touring-plans | title=Against Me! Leave Sire Records, Address Cancelled Tour Issues, And Announce Touring Plans | author=McEachnie, Patrick | publisher=The1stfive.com | date = November 28, 2010 | accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref> As 2011 unfolded, the arrangement looked to possibly be more permanent.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.spin.com/articles/watch-against-me-rehearse-new-drummer | title=Watch: Against Me! Rehearse with New Drummer | author=Gaston, Peter | magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | date=January 13, 2011 | accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> Weinberg also sat in a bit with the band [[Fences (band)|Fences]] during 2011.  In late 2011, Against Me! began recording their first album with Weinberg on drums.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.punknews.org/article/45339 | title=Against Me! beginning work on next album | publisher=Punknews.org | date=November 29, 2011 | accessdate=2012-03-17}}</ref> However, in December 2012, Weinberg announced via Twitter, without notifying the other members beforehand, that he was leaving Against Me!.<ref name=\"am-leave\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/against_me_drummer_jay_weinberg_quits_band.html?no_takeover | title=Against Me! Drummer Jay Weinberg Quits Band | author=LeMoine, Adam | publisher=[[Ultimate-Guitar.com]] | date=December 20, 2012 | accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref> Using Twitter, he wished the band well, but the other members in return tweeted a picture of a [[drum machine]].<ref name=\"am-leave\"/>\n\n==Slipknot==\n[[File:Slipknot - The Grey Chapter Tour 2016 - D\u00fcsseldorf - 01698151 - Leonhard Kreissig - Canon EOS 5D Mark II.jpg|thumb|Weinberg performing with [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] in 2016.]]\nIn 2014, Weinberg became the drummer for [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] following the departure of [[Joey Jordison]] in late 2013. Although the drummer's identity had not been officially revealed by the band itself, preferring to keep the identity of the new members (a new bassist, confirmed to be [[Alessandro Venturella]], had also joined the band) a secret as they were not official members at that time; a former drum technician for the band leaked their itinerary, revealing that the drummer is Weinberg. Venturella was also named on the itinerary, though fans had identified him earlier via his distinctive hand tattoos.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://lambgoat.com/news/23734/Confirmed--Jay-Weinberg-is-Slipknots-drummer | title=Confirmed: Jay Weinberg is Slipknot's drummer | date=December 3, 2014 | accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref> Weinberg was eventually officially revealed to be the drummer by [[Jim Root]] in an interview with Ultimate-Guitar on May 13, 2015.<ref>https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/jim_root_seems_like_stone_sour_cant_even_write_a_new_record_they_lost_a_good_writer.html \"So VMan and '''Jay''' both came to my house and we started rehearsing a couple weeks early before we went on the tour. I sat down with VMan and we really dissected all the songs from the set we were gonna play live and dissected not just the album versions but the live versions and how Paul would approach these songs.\"</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''The Reveling''' \n* ''The Reveling'' (2008)\n* ''3D Radio'' (2009) <small>(EP)</small>\n\n'''[[Madball]]'''\n* ''[[Empire (Madball album)|Empire]]'' (2010)\n\n'''[[Against Me!]]'''\n* \"[[Russian Spies / Occult Enemies]]\" (2011) <small>(Non-album single)</small>\n\n'''[[Hesitation Wounds]]''' \n* ''Hesitation Wounds'' (2013) <small>(EP)</small>\n* ''Awake For Everything'' (2016)\n\n'''[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]'''\n* ''[[.5: The Gray Chapter]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Day of the Gusano: Live in Mexico|Day of the Gusano]] (2017)''\n*[[All Out Life]] (2018) <small>(Non-album single)</small>\n* ''[[We Are Not Your Kind]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100730075755/http://www.metalinjection.net/tv/view/5416/madballs-jay-weinberg-exclusive-interview 2010 Metal Injection video interview with Weinberg about joining Madball]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joey Jordison]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] [[drummer]]|years=2014-present}} \n{{s-end}}\n{{Slipknot}}\n{{Bruce Springsteen}}\n{{Madball}}\n{{Against Me!}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinberg, Jay}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American drummers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock drummers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:E Street Band members]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish heavy metal musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Middletown Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rumson-Fair Haven Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:Madball members]]\n[[Category:Against Me! members]]\n[[Category:Slipknot (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jay Weinberg\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image            = Against Me! @ Dour 2012 (7875273172).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| caption          = Jay Weinberg performing with [[Against Me!]] in 2012.\n| birth_name       = Jay Weinberg\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Ballbag\n* J-peg\n}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1990|09|08}}\n| origin           = [[Middletown Township, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[nu metal]]\n* [[groove metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[alternative metal]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Drums\n* vocals\n}}\n| years_active     = 2000\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]\n* [[Hesitation Wounds]]\n* [[Madball]]\n* [[Against Me!]]\n* [[Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band]]\n* Bleed the Pigs \n}}\n| website          =\n}}\n\n'''Jay Weinberg''' (born September 8, 1990),<ref name=\"nsl-int\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2009/05/jay_weinberg_speaks_hockey_dru.html | title=Jay Weinberg speaks: hockey, drumming and the E Street Band | author=Lustig, Jay | newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]] | date=May 8, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> is an American musician and drummer for heavy metal band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]. He is the son of American drummer [[Max Weinberg]]. He has played with the American [[punk rock]] band the Reveling<ref name=rs>{{cite magazine|title=Springsteen's \"Secret Weapon\": How Jay Weinberg Scored a Spot in the E Street Band |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/03/27/springsteens-secret-weapon-how-jay-weinberg-scored-a-spot-in-the-e-street-band/ |date=March 27, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-15 |author=Greene, Andy |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> and toured in 2009 as a drummer with [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s [[E Street Band]], substituting for his father.<ref name=yahoo>{{cite news|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/1/20090322/ten-weinberg-to-be-replaced-by-his-son-o-c60bd6d.html |title=Weinberg to be replaced by his son on Springsteen shows in Europe |date=March 22, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-15 |work=[[Yahoo News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327094709/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/1/20090322/ten-weinberg-to-be-replaced-by-his-son-o-c60bd6d.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref> During 2010, he was briefly the drummer for [[Madball]]. During 2011 and 2012, Weinberg played with [[Against Me!]]. In 2014, Weinberg replaced [[Joey Jordison]] as the drummer for [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] and is currently the youngest member of the band.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWeinberg is the son of drummer [[Max Weinberg]], who joined the E Street Band in 1975;<ref name=yahoo/> his mother, Rebecca \"Becky\" (Schick), was a former teacher.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> He grew up in [[Middletown Township, New Jersey|Middletown Township]], New Jersey.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> His mother was a [[Methodist]] and his father [[Jewish]].<ref name=\"schleier\">{{cite news | title=E Street to Conan, Max Weinberg keeps on drumming | author=Schleier, Curt | newspaper=[[Jewish Bulletin of Northern California]] | date=February 6, 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"nt100307\">{{cite news | url=http://newstranscript.gmnews.com/news/2007/1003/Front_Page/040.html | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130102185042/http://newstranscript.gmnews.com/news/2007/1003/Front_Page/040.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=January 2, 2013 | title=A good cause for purrs and paws | author=Meggitt, Jane | newspaper=[[News Transcript]] | location=Monmouth County, New Jersey | date=October 3, 2007 }}</ref> His sister is Ali Weinberg Rogin (married to [[Josh Rogin]]).<ref name=Wedding>[http://washingtonlife.com/2016/04/18/society-weddings-ali-weinberg-and-josh-rogin/ Washington Life: \"Society Weddings: Ali Weinberg and Josh Rogin\" by John Arundel] April 18, 2016</ref> As a child, he played travel team [[ice hockey]] as a [[goaltender]].<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/><ref name=rs/><ref name=\"mst050909\">{{cite news | url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/44553222.html | title=The beat goes on | author=Bream, Jon | newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] | date=May 9, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-11 | page=1E | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007001745/http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/music/44553222.html | archivedate=October 7, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> At age 9 he first saw the E Street Band on their 1999\u20132000 [[Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band Reunion Tour|Reunion Tour]],<ref name=rs/> and saw shows on this and subsequent tours, especially in Europe.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> Around the same time his father took him to [[Ozzfest]] to see [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], which gave him a strong affinity for [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and other intense music genres;<ref name=mtv/> his father also exposed him to a wide variety of other music.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> He began playing guitar at age 9, bass at age 12 or 13.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/> He then started playing drums at age 14, getting only few lessons from his father without much instruction and being mostly self-taught,<ref name=rs/><ref name=\"nsl051509\"/><ref name=\"nsl081309\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nj.com/insidejersey/index.ssf/2009/08/new_gig_same_beat.html#more | title=New Gig, but Same Beat for Drummer Max Weinberg | author=Tsai, Martin | newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]] | date=August 13, 2009 | accessdate=September 5, 2009}}</ref> using his father's old gear.<ref name=mtv/> By the next year he had performed a guest appearance on stage with band [[The Used]] and subsequently with [[punk rock]]ers [[the Bouncing Souls]].<ref name=rs/> He played in the New Jersey metal band Chaosis.<ref name=\"mst050909\"/> He attended [[Rumson-Fair Haven Regional High School]] where he played on the hockey team for a time, played in a band called Sadie Mae, and graduated in 2008.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/><ref name=\"nsl051509\"/>\n\nWeinberg graduated from [[Stevens Institute of Technology]] in [[New Jersey]] in 2014.<ref name=mtv>{{cite web |title=Jay Weinberg Feels 'Super Fortunate' To Play on Bruce Springsteen Tour |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1610571/20090504/springsteen_bruce.jhtml |date=May 4, 2009 |accessdate=2009-05-15 |author=Wolfson, Melanie |publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MORE PHOTOS: Stevens graduates, including son of celebrity drummer, told to 'remain optimistic' |url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2014/05/more_photos_stevens_graduates_including_celebrity_drummer_told_to_remain_optimistic.html |date=2014-05-22 |author=Hortillosa, Summer Dawn |work=[[The Jersey Journal]] |accessdate=2015-12-29}}</ref> He joined the New York punk band the Reveling in August 2008, which plays before small audiences in venues such as the Ace of Clubs nightspot in Manhattan, various spots in Brooklyn, and elsewhere.<ref name=\"nsl-int\"/><ref name=\"nsl051509\"/><ref name=\"ct061609\">{{cite news | url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/about-last-night/2009/06/springsteen-didnt-look-far-for-teenage-drummer-jay-weinberg.html | title=Springsteen didn't look far for teenage drummer, Jay Weinberg | author=Arroyave, Luis | newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=June 16, 2009 | accessdate=2009-07-31}}</ref> With them he does some of the band's songwriting and arranging.<ref name=\"nsl051509\"/>\n\n==Appearances with Springsteen==\n[[File:Max watches Jay Weinberg 2008.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Max Weinberg (standing in front of stage, in black shirt) watches son Jay on the video screen, during \"Born to Run\" at Giants Stadium in 2008]]\nJay Weinberg's first appearance with Springsteen was in the summer of 2008, filling in for his father on \"[[Born to Run (song)|Born to Run]]\" at [[Giants Stadium]] after having watched many other performances during the [[Magic Tour (Bruce Springsteen)|Magic Tour]].<ref name=rs/> Springsteen's 2009 [[Working on a Dream Tour]] posed a problem for Max Weinberg, as ''[[The Tonight Show with Conan O'Brien]]'' in Los Angeles \u2013 for which he was [[the Max Weinberg 7]] bandleader \u2013 was starting at the same time that the tour would be in progress.<ref name=\"bs-max09\">{{cite news | url=http://www.backstreets.com/news.html | title=Max Watch '09: A Tale of Two Bosses | publisher=[[Backstreets.com]] | date=January 16, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> Springsteen's manager [[Jon Landau]] viewed Weinberg as the \"secret weapon\" to substitute for his father without losing fan satisfaction.<ref name=rs/> Both Landau and E Street guitarist [[Steve Van Zandt]] attributed Jay Weinberg's skills to a genetic gift.<ref name=rs/><ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/03/springsteen-wei.html | title=Springsteen news: Steve Van Zandt talks about the E Street Band's new drummer | author=Brunner, Rob | magazine=[[EW.com]] | date=March 20, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref>\n\nOnce the initial portion of the tour began in early April 2009, Weinberg played from several songs to half the show on most of the dates.<ref name=mtv/><ref name=\"ct061609\"/><ref name=\"pl042209\">{{cite news | url=http://www.patriotledger.com/entertainment/x50626460/Boss-and-band-cover-a-lot-of-ground-in-Boston | title=Boss and band cover a lot of ground in Boston | author=Miller, Jay N. | newspaper=[[The Patriot Ledger]] | date=April 22, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref><ref name=\"gnr050409\">{{cite news | url=http://www.news-record.com/content/2009/05/03/article/3_hour_show_rocks_steensboro | archive-url=https://archive.is/20090505165230/http://www.news-record.com/content/2009/05/03/article/3_hour_show_rocks_steensboro | url-status=dead | archive-date=May 5, 2009 | title=Review: 3-hour show rocks 'Steensboro' | author=Puterbaugh, Parke | publisher=[[News & Record (Greensboro)|News & Record]] | date=May 4, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-10 }}</ref> He received a very positive reaction from both audiences and reviewers as a re-energizing \"spark plug\"<ref name=\"gnr050409\"/> for the much-older band,<ref name=\"atu051509\"/> with his vigorous, long-hair-flying style inviting comparisons to [[Dave Grohl]]<ref name=\"mc050209\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/music/all-d4_weekconcerts.6882370may02,0,2402026.story \n |title=Concert Reviews: Bruce Springsteen \n |author=Gehman, Geoff \n |newspaper=[[The Morning Call]] \n |date=May 2, 2009 \n |accessdate=2009-05-10 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521110511/http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/music/all-d4_weekconcerts.6882370may02%2C0%2C2402026.story \n |archivedate=May 21, 2009 \n}}</ref> and his potential for replacing his father drawing allusions to [[Wally Pipp]].<ref name=\"mst050909\"/><ref name=\"pl042209\"/> He began playing complete shows in mid-May 2009 during the tour's American first leg, as his father went to California to prepare test runs for ''The Tonight Show'' start.<ref name=\"nsl051509\"/><ref name=\"atu051509\">{{cite news | url=http://blogs.timesunion.com/reviews/?p=900 | title=Bruce Springsteen @ Times Union Center 5/14/09 | author=Eck, Michael | newspaper=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]] | date=May 15, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518180059/http://blogs.timesunion.com/reviews/?p=900 | archivedate=May 18, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' magazine's editor said that a college freshman playing on one of the year's biggest rock tours is \"certainly a unique story\".<ref name=\"nsl051509\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2009/05/born_to_drum_two_generations_o.html | title=Born To Drum: Two generations of Weinbergs do the E Street Shuffle | author=Lustig, Jay | newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]] | date=May 15, 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> Weinberg played a number of dates early on in the European second leg of the tour, including at the Dutch [[Pinkpop festival]] in [[Landgraaf]], the [[Netherlands]] in addition to [[Bonnaroo]] in [[Manchester, Tennessee]].  He also played during a few dates of the American third and final leg.  When not needed for the Springsteen tour, he continued to play for the Reveling, often before audiences that were three orders of magnitude smaller; he said of the difference, \"I liked the duality of it all ... I like doing this just as much as I like doing that.\"<ref name=\"ct061609\"/>\n\n==Madball==\nIn February 2010, Weinberg began playing with [[Madball]], a legendary hardcore band based out of New York City.<ref name=\"prp-mad\"/> In June of that year, it was announced that he would become the drummer for their upcoming album ''[[Empire (Madball album)|Empire]]'' and a tour.<ref name=\"prp-mad\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theprp.com/2010/06/25/news/madball-recruit-new-drummer/ | title=Madball Recruit New Drummer | publisher=ThePRP.com | date=June 25, 2010 | accessdate=2010-06-25}}</ref> However, in September 2010 the group discharged him, with Madball vocalist [[Freddy Cricien]] saying, \"I'm letting Jay go [mid-tour] in Canada because I just feel he doesn't represent this band well on a character level.\"<ref name=\"blab1\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=146430 |title=Madball Fires Max Weinberg's Son |date=September 21, 2010 |accessdate=2010-09-21 |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926153955/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=146430 |archivedate=September 26, 2010 |df= }}</ref> In response, Weinberg said that he had already quit the group by that time, and that \"while I really enjoyed playing the music, I do not subscribe to their choice of habits and lifestyle. This past August while on tour in Europe, disturbing events within the band indicated to me that it was time for me to move on.\"<ref name=\"blab2\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=147874 | title=Ex-Madball Drummer Jay Weinberg Says He Quit The Band | date=October 18, 2010 | publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] | accessdate=2010-10-18 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022140111/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=147874 | archivedate=October 22, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In any case, Weinberg said both he and the group should be proud of ''Empire''.<ref name=\"blab2\"/>\n\n==Against Me!==\nIn November 2010, it was announced that Weinberg would be playing drums with punk rock band [[Against Me!]] for their upcoming 2011 shows, covering for regular drummer George Rebelo while he tours with his other band, [[Hot Water Music]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.the1stfive.com/news/against-me-leave-sire-records-address-cancelled-tour-issues-and-announce-touring-plans | title=Against Me! Leave Sire Records, Address Cancelled Tour Issues, And Announce Touring Plans | author=McEachnie, Patrick | publisher=The1stfive.com | date = November 28, 2010 | accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref> As 2011 unfolded, the arrangement looked to possibly be more permanent.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.spin.com/articles/watch-against-me-rehearse-new-drummer | title=Watch: Against Me! Rehearse with New Drummer | author=Gaston, Peter | magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | date=January 13, 2011 | accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> Weinberg also sat in a bit with the band [[Fences (band)|Fences]] during 2011.  In late 2011, Against Me! began recording their first album with Weinberg on drums.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.punknews.org/article/45339 | title=Against Me! beginning work on next album | publisher=Punknews.org | date=November 29, 2011 | accessdate=2012-03-17}}</ref> However, in December 2012, Weinberg announced via Twitter, without notifying the other members beforehand, that he was leaving Against Me!.<ref name=\"am-leave\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/against_me_drummer_jay_weinberg_quits_band.html?no_takeover | title=Against Me! Drummer Jay Weinberg Quits Band | author=LeMoine, Adam | publisher=[[Ultimate-Guitar.com]] | date=December 20, 2012 | accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref> Using Twitter, he wished the band well, but the other members in return tweeted a picture of a [[drum machine]].<ref name=\"am-leave\"/>\n\n==Slipknot==\n[[File:Slipknot - The Grey Chapter Tour 2016 - D\u00fcsseldorf - 01698151 - Leonhard Kreissig - Canon EOS 5D Mark II.jpg|thumb|Weinberg performing with [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] in 2016.]]\nIn 2014, Weinberg became the drummer for [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] following the departure of [[Joey Jordison]] in late 2013. Although the drummer's identity had not been officially revealed by the band itself, preferring to keep the identity of the new members (a new bassist, confirmed to be [[Alessandro Venturella]], had also joined the band) a secret as they were not official members at that time; a former drum technician for the band leaked their itinerary, revealing that the drummer is Weinberg. Venturella was also named on the itinerary, though fans had identified him earlier via his distinctive hand tattoos.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://lambgoat.com/news/23734/Confirmed--Jay-Weinberg-is-Slipknots-drummer | title=Confirmed: Jay Weinberg is Slipknot's drummer | date=December 3, 2014 | accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref> Weinberg was eventually officially revealed to be the drummer by [[Jim Root]] in an interview with Ultimate-Guitar on May 13, 2015.<ref>https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/jim_root_seems_like_stone_sour_cant_even_write_a_new_record_they_lost_a_good_writer.html \"So VMan and '''Jay''' both came to my house and we started rehearsing a couple weeks early before we went on the tour. I sat down with VMan and we really dissected all the songs from the set we were gonna play live and dissected not just the album versions but the live versions and how Paul would approach these songs.\"</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''The Reveling''' \n* ''The Reveling'' (2008)\n* ''3D Radio'' (2009) <small>(EP)</small>\n\n'''[[Madball]]'''\n* ''[[Empire (Madball album)|Empire]]'' (2010)\n\n'''[[Against Me!]]'''\n* \"[[Russian Spies / Occult Enemies]]\" (2011) <small>(Non-album single)</small>\n\n'''[[Hesitation Wounds]]''' \n* ''Hesitation Wounds'' (2013) <small>(EP)</small>\n* ''Awake For Everything'' (2016)\n\n'''[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]'''\n* ''[[.5: The Gray Chapter]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Day of the Gusano: Live in Mexico|Day of the Gusano]] (2017)''\n*[[All Out Life]] (2018) <small>(Non-album single)</small>\n* ''[[We Are Not Your Kind]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100730075755/http://www.metalinjection.net/tv/view/5416/madballs-jay-weinberg-exclusive-interview 2010 Metal Injection video interview with Weinberg about joining Madball]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joey Jordison]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] [[drummer]]|years=2014-present}} \n{{s-end}}\n{{Slipknot}}\n{{Bruce Springsteen}}\n{{Madball}}\n{{Against Me!}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinberg, Jay}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American drummers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock drummers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:E Street Band members]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish heavy metal musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Middletown Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rumson-Fair Haven Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:Madball members]]\n[[Category:Against Me! members]]\n[[Category:Slipknot (band) members]]\n", "name_user": "116.86.141.7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Weinberg"}
